    "body": "## Problem\n\nSome commands such as `gh` try to query the tty, and will hang/timeout until a query response. For `jobstart(pty=true)` the response never arrives, so the command behaves wrong.\n\nThere is a [workaround](https://github.com/justinmk/neovim/blob/0000890f0800e09c6f64b008455a4eb02cfccb19/runtime/doc/api.txt#L1282-L1299) which gets clumsy when orchestrating multiple such processes: for each job, hook up a channel between `jobstart{pty=true}` + `nvim_open_term{on_input}`.\n\nBuffers are a basic user-facing concept that users may add marks to, etc. Plugins shouldn't have to destroy terminal-display buffers to \"update\" them with the output of potentially multiple jobs. And they shouldn't have to cobble together shell-specific job orchestration.\n\n```lua\nlocal chan\nlocal job\nchan = vim.api.nvim_open_term(buf, {\n  on_input = function(_, _, _, data)\n    -- Forward the terminal's output to the child's stdin.\n    vim.fn.chansend(job, data)\n  end,\n})\njob = vim.fn.jobstart(cmd, {\n  pty = true,\n  on_stdout = function(_, data)\n    -- Forward the child's stdout to the terminal.\n    vim.api.nvim_chan_send(chan, table.concat(data, '\\n'))\n  end,\n})\n```\n\n### Use-case\n\n- [example](https://github.com/justinmk/guh.nvim/pull/67): run multiple commands concurrently, and then append their results to a pty or terminal buffer.\n\n\n## Expected behavior\n\n- `jobstart(buf = existing :terminal buffer)`\n\n## Existing (working) features\n\n<details>\n<summary>Existing (working) features</summary>\n\n\nPlugins can reuse terminal buffers. This is nice for apps like [guh.nvim](https://github.com/justinmk/guh.nvim) , which want to show some CLI output and reuse the buffer to \"refresh\" the output:\n\n```lua\nvim.fn.jobstart({'gh','status'}, {term=true})\n-- gh exits...\n\n-- plugin can overwrite the buffer\nvim.cmd[[set nomodified]]\nvim.fn.jobstart({'gh','status'}, {term=true})\n```\n\n</details>",
